European inflation slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying growth in the price of food products.
The rise in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 countries of the euro area, registering - after the 2.6 percent of the month of October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Statistical Office of the Union based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts gave only 3 percent as likely, Bloomberg said.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, on the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and the reduction in forced unemployment, would trigger an inflation spiral.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the trap of 22: "negotiating" on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue later.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the 12-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation has skyrocketed in the euro area as a result of galloping food and energy prices.
Wheat futures prices increased by 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching almost $100 a barrel as early as last month.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while in 2009 it will drop to 1.9 percent.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent in the next 3 or 4 months, but the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to double interest rates during 2008.
Gallup predicts a government crisis
After a long stagnation, by early December the support of the Young Democrats Alliance increased significantly, reaching its peak since 2002, while the Gallup had never before experienced such a low – 13 percent – level in the case of the Socialists.
The difference in the case of safe party voters - due to the greater firmness of opposition voters - would mean support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) versus support of a fifth for socialists (20 percent).
According to the survey, the Democratic Forum and the Alliance of Free Democrats would not reach even the limit necessary to have any parliamentary seat: their support within the entire population is two percent.
Among the safe voters there are one percent more sympathizers on both sides.
The economic environment continued to deteriorate even compared to the previous lowest point - it has never been so high, 41 percent the proportion of those who judged the country's economic situation especially bad, while another 46 percent believe the situation is quite bad.
Families, after the most hopeful expectations of spring and summer, are now more pessimistic about changing their own economic situation.
As far as next year is concerned, the majority of the population is in worsening condition and only one-tenth expects improvement.
In December, 71 percent of those polled, more than any previous Gallup poll, felt that the President was performing poorly rather than well.
13 percent of respondents trust or rely heavily on Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny, while Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n has the support of 38 percent of respondents.
54 percent of the population does not trust the head of government at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of the Young Democrats Alliance.
One of the indicators of the configuration of the political situation is that, what proportion of society thinks it is possible to control the discontent experienced with the person of the Head of Government without a change of government.
While after the October riots last year 35 percent thought it would be desirable to keep the government and the head of government in power, currently this proportion is only 20 percent, while the relative majority (33 percent) believe that the only solution is to hold new elections.
Interest in the referendum is characterized by the fact that 60 percent of respondents to the participation question answered that they would certainly participate and another 20 percent said that they are likely to participate.
By comparison, only 55 percent of the population would participate in "a general election to be held this Sunday" and another 15 percent believe their participation is likely. Based on the current intentions of the voters, there is no doubt about the result of the popular poll.
Seventy-four percent of the population would disapprove of the payment of tuition fees, 79 percent would disapprove of the medical consultation service and 84 percent would disapprove of hospital care.
If we looked at these proportions only among the safe participants in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of study rights, payment for medical consultations and hospital care.
The most expensive is the Auchan, Tesco has fivefold its prices
The average price level increase of 16 percent was maintained by the hypermarkets of the Budaörs gold trading triangle, with the difference that VAT has not been increased this year.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g
This year, the usual Christmas basket of the Napi newspaper also increased by an average of 16 percent in the Budaörs gold commercial triangle, but in all hypermarkets growth was recorded well above the thousand HUF.
As prices in food supermarkets had already “fired” in December last year, there was no dramatic percentage increase compared to the high starting point.
However, it is obviously frightening for consumers that what they were able to buy last year at a price well below nine thousand HUF, today they cannot do it for ten thousand.
The Napi basket in the hypermarkets studied exceeded the psychological limit of ten thousand HUF with a minimum of 91 HUF.
And the highest value basket was 10 573 HUF.
(in 2003 that basket cost 6800 HUF.)
The price of Unicum liquor and fish remained almost at the level of the previous year, but there was a sharp increase in turkey breast fillet, nut and poppy seed.
The price of wheat flour and bread followed the data of the Central Bureau of Statistics, although in Auchan we have also found a kilo of bread for the price of 139 HUF.
The competition did not reduce the price of the product to less than 200 HUF.
It was equally surprising in this store that the price of Coca-Cola with a two-litre bottle cost less than 200 HUF, so this product, even with the price of the bottle, cost only 257 HUF.
However, in the basket of Napi Auchan was the most expensive, while Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, compared to last year’s Christmas prices, Cora increased by 15, while Tesco and Auchan increased by about 18 percent the prices listed in Napi’s basket.
Comparing the values of last year’s most expensive basket with that of this year’s cheapest basket, the difference has been 12 percent, while the growth between last year’s cheapest and this year’s most expensive basket has been 21 percent.
The average growth was 1480 HUF.
Last year the average price growth was 1206 HUF, so during Christmas last year in prices was felt the increase in VAT.
It was precisely this process that shattered trade, supermarkets were visibly unable to decide on the price margin to be applied for each product and to calculate the effect of the change in prices on consumption.
(If the trader misplans the speed of a product’s circulation, you may lose a significant profit in the margin that fits the sales volume.)
The increase in the price of the Napi basket reached such extremes as a result of the increase in VAT, that the most expensive was higher with 1720 HUF than the value recorded in 2006, while in the cheapest the difference was only 844 HUF.
Such extremes did not occur this year, as the highest price now has been 1630 HUF more than last year and the cheapest also increased by 1284 HUF.
Comparing the two holiday seasons, catastrophic growth in prices was recorded in less than 20 months, in hypermarkets the price of essential consumer goods grew by more than 30 percent.
(However, this does not necessarily confirm the figures of the Central Bureau of Statistics: this office, in the case of some basic necessities food recorded in the 12-month interval a price increase of more than 30 percent.
So for example, in addition to wheat, also in the case of the egg.)
According to the Napi basket, in the latter case this seems almost impossible, because in the price of this product that was quite expensive already last year compared to the base, there was, in the worst case, only a 10 percent increase in prices.
According to all the indices, flour suppliers have a stronger position than egg suppliers, and can impose the drastic increase in prices even on multinationals.
Hypermarkets do not complain in the gold trading triangle, they constantly talk about positive results.
According to our collected experiences, most of the consumers in the three stores visited are no longer interested in prices.
Of all the products they buy large quantities, taking by pallets the preserved food.
On Wednesday morning, the three stores formed large queues in front of the boxes because the number of customers suddenly increased.
However, we have information that in the country sales volumes are lower, numerous multinationals complain to survey institutes because revenues are below their plans and not only in the case of food, but also in that of household appliances.
In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, several thousand infections caused primarily by the misuse of antibiotics have been recorded in hospitals.
The prevailing hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and staff overload do not favor infection control - says the head of the medical department of the National Center for Epidemiology.
In many hospitals it is saved even with disinfectants.
A MRSA infection has recently been diagnosed in the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
A person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon afterwards had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then it has not been possible to perform a major surgical intervention due to the presence of the bacteria in his body.
As of December 10 this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multidrug-resistant agents have been reported in the National Nosocomialis Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Center for Epidemiology.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections caused by multi-resistant agents has been safely recorded, otherwise no information is available.
About two-thirds (683 cases) of infections are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, which is resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry the bacterium Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once over- or unduly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics turn into highly antibiotic-resistant bacteria and quickly become infected in inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicemia in the first place to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with a weakened body, to the elderly or to people of low weight.
In the opinion of the chief medical officer of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the nursing staff treats them in rubber gloves and mask, and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment," said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are pre-examined to check for MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It is not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital MRSA infections in most cases, however the current national hospital circumstances do not favor the prevention of formation and contagion with multi-resistant pathogens - says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals it is not fashionable to take microbiological samples.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not fund these medical examinations.
So most of the cases come to light when the already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient - said the doctor-in-chief of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes stringent commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological conditions.
Efforts should be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Taking microbiological samples are even less common in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
It is saved with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is transmitted from one patient to another through healthcare personnel.
Therefore, hand washing, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this regard considerable faults are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through drop-borne transmission and direct contact between people, however in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated by at least a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in the hospitals of less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher probability of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where appropriate preventive measures are implemented, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Program Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so in all countries it is fought against.
In England, for example, there is a government program to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
Apparently the program is successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and hospital infections due to these pathogens.
