The U.S. Federal Reserve, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks decided to fight together against the financial market crisis.
More than one hundred billion dollars will be received through tenders.
In these tenders, banks auction the interest rates at which they are able to lend money.
For example, the US Fed will send to bid forty billion dollars, and then another twenty-four billion will be provided by the central banks of Europe and Switzerland.
After the September 11 attacks, it is the first time that central banks from different states have agreed on this coordinated process to protect and mitigate the consequences of the financial crisis.
“This step must solve the biggest economic problem, that is, the continued growth of the free capital shortage that banks could lend,” wrote Bernard Baumohl of consulting firm Economic Outlook Group in his report to clients.
“This coordinated action by the central banks probably lowered the recession in the United States from 65 percent to fifty percent,” Baumohl said in his report.
Banks have already spent sixty billion dollars on unpaid loans, especially in the United States.
Economists still expect billions in losses.
“Central banks should really be afraid of what awaits them when they decide to take this step,” said ABN Amro chief economist Kieran Davies.
“It looks like the situation is really bad,” he added.
Central banks fear that they will have the same problems of access to loans and that they will therefore have to lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and send the U.S. economy into recession with different impacts on the growth of the world economy.
The central banks thus decided, after failing to reduce the so-called LIBOR rate, the London interbank rate used for money lending in the interbank market.
This means that banks were constantly afraid to borrow money even when the central banks of the US, Canada and Britain lowered their interest rates several times during the fall.
"It will have the same effect as another interest rate drop," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
