New gas fears between Russia and Ukraine
The growing dispute over gas prices between Ukraine and Russia increases the risk that Russia’s export of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
Most of the gas exported by Russia to the European Union (EU) is directed through Ukraine, so each friction between the two nations is a source of attention.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises the price of gas, Russia will have to pay higher transit rates.
A dispute earlier last year reduced supplies to EU states.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow came with the Ukrainian government and the Russian state, the monopoly owner of the gas, Gazprom, trying to agree on how much money Ukraine should pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom said it will charge Ukraine more, as Ukraine has pledged to pay an extra 50% in 2008 for gas coming from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say it could be that Ukraine will pay 40% more for Gazprom’s imports.
“It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important transits for gas during the talks,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinakh told Reuters.
“Changes in gas prices should not be related to our arguments about the levels of transit rates [to Western Europe] via Ukraine.”
The last major gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev, Gazprom cut off supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This meant a drop in exports to Western Europe, which quickly raised prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the EU’s supply.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it is not yet fully developed.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own gas supply from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet nations of Central Asia.
NHS "will have to test foreign workers"
The Scottish NHS needs to monitor criminal records of employees from outside Europe, a watchdog said.
Auditor General Robert Black’s recommendation came after it was found that a foreign doctor was linked to the attack on Glasgow airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish NHS has no exact idea of the amount of foreign staff it has.
However, his report pointed to other checks that are carried out correctly through a sample of five health authorities.
The auditor-general checked the amount of foreign staff hired outside the European Economic Area, following the attacks on Glasgow airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at Paisley’s Royal Alexandra Hospital, was arrested at the airport after crashing a jeep at the gates of the airport terminal building.
He was one of three doctors who acted at the Old Bailey by video conferencing in October, accused in connection with the alleged car bombings in the UK.
NHS expects to carry out pre-employment checks on candidates, to make sure they meet the qualifications, experience and authorization to work in the UK.
Although the Scottish Health Board uses “Disclosure Scotland” to conduct criminal background checks, the agency has no jurisdiction to obtain this information outside of the UK.
The Auditor General’s report recommends, among other measures, that boards should rely on guidance from the Criminal Records Bureau, which helps employers with criminal controls in many countries outside the UK.
“Although we found some of the personal records with evidence of these controls, this is not a routine review,” the report says.
Black states that the Scottish NHS has a high level of compliance with its own employment policies, but notes that: "Our report highlights areas that can be improved to ensure that the necessary information is available in the NHS's foreign staff number."
BMA Scotland President Dr Peter Terry said it was "very unlikely" that pre-employment checks could identify potential NHS employees who could commit terrorist acts in the future.
“The report suggests that pre-employment checks work in NHS Scotland but it is not clear what the added value of the recommendations made is,” he explained.
Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign people, most of them doctors and nurses.
But the auditor-general warned that the number may be higher, in part because boards have trouble identifying which employees have indefinite residence permits.
The investigation also found that the verification procedures established by NHS authorities in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire and Lothian were being widely complied with.
This includes passport checks, work permits and qualification checks.
The Scottish government is currently reviewing the foreign nationals’ pre-employment policy and guideline at the NHS.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I had a great interest in this work being carried out in the wake of the Glasgow airport terrorist attack.
He added that the Scottish government, in conjunction with the health boards, could consider the recommendations of the reports and that this will be reflected in the update of the pre-employment control guidelines for all working groups - including foreigners - that they planned to publish next month.
