Is the subprime mortgage crisis infecting the American credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, it is natural that some dorsal fins swim excitedly around.
Today that the American housing market is in crisis, predators have their eyes set on the country’s credit card market.
Analysts at Goldman Sachs estimate that credit card losses can reach $99 million if the subprime mortgage crisis infects other forms of consumer credit.
Signs of contagion are already seen.
There is an increase in both card charges and crime rates, which measures the proportion of balances that have not been amortized or that have more than 30 days delay respectively.
HSBC announced last month that it has taken over 1.4 million bucks in its U.S. consumer finance business, in part due to the weakness of card borrowers.
However, it is too early for panic.
Delinquency and delinquency are at low levels.
According to Moody’s, a rating agency, in the third quarter the crime rate of 3.89% was almost a percentage point below the historical average.
The deterioration in rates can be explained in part by technical factors.
A change in the U.S. Bankruptcy Law of Persons (2005) resulted in a sharp drop in bankruptcy applications, which in turn represent a large loss on credit cards; the number of applications (and therefore delinquency) would be growing again, or it may happen that conditions for borrowers were worsening.
The industry also reports strong payment rates, which show how much of its debts consumers pay each month.
And trust in credit cards and asset-backed securities is pretty firm, despite paralysis in other financial areas.
Dennis Moroney of TowerGroup, a research firm, predicts emission volumes for 2007 will be about 25% higher than last year.
The direct channels of infection of the crisis between subprime mortgages and the credit card market certainly exist: consumers like to charge credit card debt now that credit institutions are expiring.
But credit card issuers look more at the flow of liquidity than asset values, so falling prices don’t necessarily trigger a change in borrowers’ lending capacity.
They can even work to advance the issuers.
Incentives for consumers to continue to amortize the mortgage decreases if the properties are worth less than the value of the loan; and as a result, the payment of the card’s debt rises in the list of priorities.
Card issuers can also respond quickly and flexibly to difficult conditions as mortgage lenders, changing interest rates or altering credit balances.
That, in theory, should reduce the risk of a rapid restocking of assets.
“We’re not going to wake up one day and re-evaluate all the loans,” said Gary Perlin, chief financial officer at Capital One.
If a sudden subprime infection in the credit card market is unlikely, the risks of a sustained decline are much more real.
If house prices are lower and a credit crunch pushes America into recession, the industry undoubtedly faces a tougher future.
We need to keep an eye on those dorsal fins.
