Buses bring refugees back to work – and to the fight against al-Qaeda
The first buses with Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling the exiles who were left without cash, no visa extensions and those who expected the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who drove them out of their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy composed of a dozen buses, the terminal was full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport.
“I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad,” says Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I’ve read in the newspapers about what happened in Baghdad and that is safe now.”
“They say Mahdi’s army stopped killing people,” he says, referring to the Shia militia of religious militant Cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to temporarily cease.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite and teacher in the Amariyah Sunni area, returned with his two children because it was impossible to renew his visa in Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in his country.
His Shiite neighbors in Amariyah called him on the phone to tell him that an allied U.S. force helped pull al-Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of Jordan’s newcomers was the head of a Sunni and Shiite tribe who had been driven from their home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack after urging citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Al Qaeda militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my comrades.”
"That's why I'm back today," said 62-year-old Sabaah Alu Obeidi.
Many said they were attracted by the growing calm in the capital since U.S. troops had solidified groups of “concerned citizens,” armed and working in cooperation with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many said they have returned because of visa denial and lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, a 51-year-old father of three, voiced suspicion among exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugees’ visas to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
"We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq," he said.
“I can’t believe in a government that supports the criminals who set my house on fire after I left it.”
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that Sunnis have been expelled from Shiite areas and vice versa, relaxing tensions.
There is a fear that a sudden wave of refugees will resurrect sectarian tensions and start the struggle.
