Venus is the twin brother of Earth.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not yet been raised. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and whirlwinds in the poles, the same ones that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers had suspected that rays might exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays are silent from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California, Los Angeles, to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous Urey-Miller model of the origin of life, rays caused life on Earth: storms could have caused reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it’s not like that: if there were life there one day, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500°C prevail on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures below zero can be reached.
“Possibly, Venus is an Earth’s ‘diabolical’ twin, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research of this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for the research of Venus.
The latest findings of research that will be presented in many Nature articles, according to the researchers, underscore not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more in common with Earth than we had assumed,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the south polar region a vortex formed by clouds that spins faster.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the Earth's poles, as described by a team of researchers by Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to the Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers is almost as large.
This planet also called the dawn star or evening star orbits the Sun for nearly 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: one day on Venus equals 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bars does not closely resemble Earth, scientists start from the premise that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
The two planets had agglomerated water that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it dissociated into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had become carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
