It's not the wooden boxes.
Whoever relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but doesn’t think of Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
Currently the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's list of works.
Most of the ninety-four Bright-Box "type" on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" raised doubts about the authenticity of Brillo-Boxes from the year 1968 of Andy Warhol, the museum Moderna Museet in Stockholm carried out internal research and came to disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillio-Boxes", that the former director of the museum Moderna and the museum "Pontus H" are in fact a falcon.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Bright-Boxes" in New York, painted the wooden boxes in red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had "Bright" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, at the 1968 exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet, hundreds of cardboard boxes were exhibited. These were not made by Warhol (due to expenses), but were brought directly from the "Brillo" cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but exhibited specimens (which were only objects).
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed to produce wooden boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited at the Modern Museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auctions as originals of the "Bright-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
At auctions, some of them were purchased for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous director of the Pontus Hultén museum made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes that Warhol left to him.
But in reality, 105 boxes were produced in the same year in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief curator of the Museum Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm. They were first printed and grinded their tight plates and then painted them to oil with the brush.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the paint was applied with a roller without directly printing the pressed silvers. In addition, it is not about oil paint, but about acrylic paint.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and must be removed from Andy Warhol's official list of Brilliant-Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet Museum and adds that if the Authentication Commission "Andy Warhol Art" in New York will not come to any conclusion, the Moderna Museet Museums will classify the copies as such.
Already in July the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these “serious allegations” that they are boxes of soap powder.
But from that moment on everything remained in absolute silence.
